		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">RangerRath wrote:</b><hr size="1" />gbaji,<br>I seek your knowledge once again.&nbsp;&nbsp;I was help a guldie get her faction to indifferent to so she could catch up with the progression tasks and mission.  We got her faction up to indifferent but ran into a problem.<br><br>When she hailed the chieftain to get the flag, he told her she is to young for the difficult tasks he would give her.  She is a 58th level cleric.<br><br>I was wondering if you knew if the progression missions are also leveled based and at what level she can start them.<br><br>TIA.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>You know? The same thing happened with a guildmember of mine this last week. Since the quest stuff was down (not sure if that's back up), I wasn't able to check on level requirements.<br><br>I do suspect that the chieftan will not &quot;recruit&quot; you unless you are 65th level or higher. All I can say for sure is that I was able to get the character flag at level 66 (which allowed me to talk to private whoever and get solo tasks), but a level 61 got that same &quot;you're too young&quot; message not 30 minutes later.<br><br>I don't have any confirmation of this, but that would seem to be the case. Honestly, you'll have a hell of a time doing those solo tasks at a lower level anyway (aside from the &quot;kill 11 goblin laborers in stillmoon&quot; one I suppose).<br><br>As to the wayfarers solo tasks, I honestly found them *very* hard to do solo. As a level 66 paladin I *could* single kill the mobs, but it was really really slow and annoying. The lavaspider thingies were a pain to get to and the pathing of the mobs guaranteed that you'd get a higher level &quot;rare&quot; mob coming from one direction or another before you could collect the silks you needed. The best one seemed to be the &quot;kill 20&quot; mission in stillmoon, but I honestly gave up after like 2 solo kills since it was waaaay too slow doing it alone. I was unlucky and found no one there at the time. Came back later and grouped up with random people there and finished it in no time.<br><br><br>And that's the really cool thing about those wayfarers solo tasks. Aside from one occasion, I've yet to log into stillmoon and see no one there at all. And since most of the people there are doing various faction quests themselves (exp isn't that got IMO), no one has any issues with inviting random people to join up. Um. This is obviously another reason to take the &quot;kill 20&quot; task instead of the goblin meat task. Folks might be less likely to invite you to join them if they know they'll have to share drops with you (unless of course none of them have that particular mission). Since all kills count for everyone, they'll always be willing to invite you if that's the mission you have. It costs them nothing.<br><br><br>Oh. One more observation. Don't forget your double exp potion you hopefully got recently. Once you start doing the second tier solo tasks (the ones from the keeper/darkreign camps), the exp reward for completion starts to get *really* huge. It's not a bad idea at all to take a drink of your potion right before you kill that last mob. I think the first solo one gave me like 1.5 bubbles of AA exp. Later tasks will give out free AAs (not sure if that's actual exp though, so that may not count). But you'll likely not get a better gain in terms of exp per use of those potions then upon completion of those tasks.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><